<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06108013 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06108013 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  CADENCE DESIGN Systems President Joe Costello either doesn't know how to playthe market, or he knows too well -- and a court may get to decide which.;   In February, Costello sold 100,000 of his shares in the San Josedesign-automation company at prices ranging from $30.05 to $30.75 each. A fewweeks later, though, the stock was selling for around $31 a share and lookedto be headed higher. That prompted the Wall Street Journal to cite Costello asan example when it ran a story April 3 saying top executives sometimes don'tknow the best time to sell their own stock.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WHO KNEW WHAT WHEN?  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Bits andamp; BytesMike Langberg, Valerie Rice, Tom Schmitz and Ron Wolf contributed to thiscolumn, which was compiled by Rory J. O'Connor.  </MEMO><TEXT>     But on the afternoon of April 3, after the market closed, Cadence announcedfirst-quarter sales and profits wouldn't meet expectations. Cadence stockdropped like a rock the next day, losing 17 percent of its value to close at$26.50.;    Last week, a shareholder sued, charging Costello and seven otherofficers and directors with illegally selling their stock because they knewbad news was ahead. Costello, meanwhile, is heeding company lawyers' advice tokeep mum.; (hbox);    TIN TOY TURNS LEAD: Two years after his Pixar Inc. wonan Academy Award for the computer-animated film &quot;Tin Toy,&quot; Steve Jobs may haveto melt little Oscar down for scrap. Pixar recently laid off 30 of 72employees working on a new program, including President Chuck Kolstad. And onFriday, Pixar shareholders will have the opportunity to get back the moneythey invested in the struggling venture.;    On March 29, Pixar's boardnotified shareholders they had approved a merger with New Pixar, whose soledirector is Jobs, who owns 90 percent of Pixar's stock. Jobs agreed to buy thecompany and all its liabilities for 18 cents a share -- an amount equal to theoriginal purchase price.;    A Pixar spokeswoman said Jobs made the offer tokeep Pixar's 200 or so other shareholders from losing their money. Pixar issaid to be deep in the red and reportedly hasn't made money since 1986, whenJobs bought it from producer George Lucas for an estimated $10 million.;(hbox);    PORTABABBLE: Folks are still guessing what Apple Computer plans tomanufacture in its new Colorado plant, but the smart money now says it will bea new light-weight portable Macintosh.;    Initial reports suggested Apple wasadding capacity to meet demand for its lower-cost Macintosh computers. ButApple officials never really said what the plant will make when it opens latethis year. Apple is apparently producing an adequate supply of low-end Macsnow, and boss John Sculley often has said Apple will have at least one newportable on the market by the end of 1991 -- a machine Apple vows to makeitself.; (hbox);    SO SUE ME: Ever-flamboyant T.J. Rodgers practicallychortled during a conference call to analysts Tuesday morning, when theCypress Semiconductor president hinted Texas Instruments and Advanced MicroDevices may have infringed two Cypress patents. The San Jose-based companyacquired the patents when it bought a manufacturing facility in Minnesota, andit has already added the patents to pending litigation against Sunnyvale-basedAMD.;    Cypress and AMD have a long history of bad blood and suits andcountersuits. Rodgers says he is talking to Dallas-based TI but doesn't havemuch hope of settlement because there is already litigation pending betweenthe two firms. &quot;We already have open warfare with AMD,&quot; he says. &quot;We'retalking to TI, but we might sue them, too.&quot;  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910417  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR